Eleven Minute Line, Maya Lin Studio, Wanås Foundation, #Wanås, #Sweden, 2004
.
In this #art work, Maya Lin was exploring the relationship between two- and three- dimensional space and the connection between prehistoric forms of the Americas and Europe. In Southeastern Ohio, where the artist grew up, there exist many #burial and effigy mounds from the time of the Hopewell and Adena #tribes - between 1000BC and 700 AD. One of the most striking is a mound in the shape of a #snake - the Serpent Mound. When European settlers first encountered these works and their accompanying artifacts, they were convinced that the forbears of the present day Native Americans could not have been sophisticated enough to produce them
.
.
In quest'opera, Maya Lin esplora la relazione tra lo spazio a due e tre dimensioni e la connessione tra le forme preistoriche delle Americhe e dell'Europa. Nell'Ohio del sud-est, dove l'artista è cresciuta, esistono molti tumuli funerari ed effigi dai tempi delle #tribù Hopewell e Adena - tra il 1000 e il 700 d.C. Uno dei più sorprendenti è un tumulo a forma di #serpente: il Serpent Mound. Quando i coloni europei incontrarono per la prima volta queste opere e i loro artefatti, furono convinti che i precursori dei nativi americani non avrebbero potuto essere abbastanza sofisticati per produrli
.
.

The Obert C. and Grace A. Tanner Humanities Center at the University of Utah presents the 2019 Tanner Lecture on Human Values given by artist and designer, Maya Lin, Wednesday, Nov. 20, 7 p.m. at Kingsbury Hall. Lin interprets the natural world through history, politics and culture, creating a body of work that balances art and architecture. Tickets are required to the free lecture and will be available on Monday, Oct. 21 at 10 a.m. at tickets.utah.edu or by calling 801-581-7100. “I am excited to welcome Maya Lin to give the first Tanner Human Values Lecture during my tenure as director of the Tanner Humanities Center,” said Erika George, Samuel D. Thurman Professor of Law. “Her minimalist memorials invite us to reflect on our place in the world, our relationships with one another as well as humanity’s relationship to the natural world.” Click the link in our bio for more information.

Maya Lin - systematic landscapes
...
“Utilizing the way in which scientists and computers see our world, drawing on images based on sonar views of the ocean floor, to aerial and satellite views of the land, I have started to create artworks that translate that technological view into sculptural forms.” (Maya Lin)
One of the most celebrated artists working in the United States, Maya Lin (b. 1959) came to prominence in 1981 with her design for the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. Generously illustrated and beautifully designed, Systematic Landscapes traces her continued fascination with geologic phenomena and topography, integrating natural contours and materials into evocative landscape sculptures such as Character of a Hill Under Glass (2002) and 11 Minute Line (2004).
As the book reveals, Lin’s earthworks and public sculptures have always developed alongside small-scale, exploratory sculptures and monumental temporary installations, such as Avalanche (1998), through which Lin evokes the physical processes that shape the earth. This important volume also introduces three major new installation works created for the "Systematic Landscapes" exhibition, along with a series of related drawings and reliefs demonstrating the expanding scope of Lin’s creative process. The largest of these installations, 2 x 4 Landscape, is composed from more than 45,000 sections of lumber placed on end that from a distance take on a pixel-like image of a hill, and close up create a form that evokes both mound and wave, earth and water.
Systematic Landscapes is of interest to newcomers to Maya Lin's work as well as to longtime enthusiasts of her unique artistic creations and stunning design work

In support of today's #GlobalClimateStrike, we are sharing this show-stopping piece “Folding the Hudson,“ 2018, by artist #MayaLin, which was featured in our 2018 exhibition "A River is A Drawing." The groundbreaking exhibition featured new works and ambitious site-specific installations that drew upon the theme of the Hudson River and underscored the artist's commitment to environmental issues and the ongoing effects of #climatechange. FLOW // Anyone know who Maya Lin is?  I didn’t until I visited this special exhibit entitled Flow @grartmuseum. She’s the one that as a student won the contest to design the Vietnam War Memorial in DC, created the Ecliptic public park in Grand Rapids and now this!  Focusing on her fascination with water and taking common building materials, she’s built these sculptures with the use of charting, mapping, and scientific research.

This particular sculpture is called Blue Lake Pass where particleboard is used to create a topographical landscape of this pass in the Rocky Mountains. Gridded by 3-foot square sections, I was able to walk through the narrow pathways and shift my perspective about the land and its geological scale.

You can find works like this and other classical and modern art all in one place right in the heart of downtown Grand Rapids.  I loved how it wasn’t an overwhelmingly large museum. With 3 main levels, there was plenty to be fascinated by without getting bored or tired which to me is 🔑. The collections also vary so greatly that it doesn’t feel monotonous either.  Great spot to add to your Grand Rapids itinerary!

#mayalin #foldingthechesapeake #installation #americaineartiste #femmeartiste #feministe les marbres scintillants coulent sur le sol et sur trois murs comme s’ils flottaient d’eux-mêmes au lieu d’être soigneusement collés en place. L’œuvre célèbre vraiment la magie de la baie de Chesapeake. Son intérêt pour les plans d’eau est le prolongement de son intérêt de longue date pour la protection de l’environnement et l’activisme, qui a commencé pendant son enfance, une période où les mesures législatives telles que la loi sur les espèces en voie de disparition . Chacun des marbres fait partie de l’ensemble, tout comme plus de 2700 espèces de plantes et d’animaux composent l’écosystème de Chesapeake.

“Whether it’s art, architecture, or memorials, I realize now that all my work is intrinsically tied to the natural landscape around us.” This week we #KaneGetEnough of American architect and sculptor, Maya Lin. Best known for her design of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C., which received the prestigious 25-Year Award from the American Institute of Architects, Lin is passionate about sustainability and using natural elements in her work. This is best represented by her work "Storm King Wavefield" at Storm King Art Center in New York, in which she used low-impact grasses and natural drainage system to create an organic, living work that continues to evolve. In 2016, she was honored with the Presidential Medal of Freedom by Barack Obama. We're inspired by Maya Lin's dedication to environmental awareness through her work, especially at a time when climate change is fiercely at the forefront in today's political landscape.

At the age of eight years old, artist Maya Lin’s father gave her a box of glass marbles. The material has since captivated her: “It was like opening a box of water," she has said. "They capture light in a way I had never seen." Check out this time-lapse video of three of our summer interns, Jodie Cen @_cyz_jodie, Lexie Liu @lexie_lxr, and Nicholas Malkemus @n_malkemus, installing Interrupted River: Penobscot with Lin’s studio assistant, James Ewert. Comprised of marbles adhered directly to the gallery wall, the installation took place over the course of three days earlier this month.
You can see this work and many more in Occupy Colby: Artists Need to Create on the Same Scale That Society Has the Capacity to Destroy, opening at the Museum this weekend.

Maya Lin’s artistic family gave her the base she needed to leap to national fame at 21, when, still a student at Yale, her design was chosen for the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington DC. She also designed the Civil Rights Memorial in Montgomery Alabama. Today she designs both art and architecture as well as writing several books. She tries to stay out of the public eye since her public works are so creative that privacy is not always possible.

Vietnam Veterans Memorial, Maya Lin, #Washington D.C., #USA 1982
.
Two black #granite walls, placed below grade, engraved in chronological order with the names of the men and women who gave their lives in the Vietnam War. At the apex where the two walls meet, the dates 1959 and 1973 (marking the beginning and end of the #war) "meet" thus closing the circle of the time span of the war. A returning veteran can find his or her own time upon the wall, making each one's experience of the memorial very personal and individual. The siting of the piece is directly related to the presence of both the Lincoln Monument and Washington Memorial, tying it physically and historically to the site
.
.
Due pareti di granito nero, poste sotto il livello del suolo, incise in ordine cronologico con i nomi degli uomini e delle donne che hanno dato la vita nella guerra del Vietnam. All'apice in cui si incontrano le due mura, le date 1959 e 1973 (che segnano l'inizio e la fine della guerra) "si incontrano" chiudendo così il cerchio del lasso di tempo della guerra. Un veterano di ritorno può trovare il proprio tempo sul muro, rendendo la propria  esperienza del memoriale molto personale e individuale. L'ubicazione dell'opera è direttamente correlata alla presenza sia del Lincoln Monument che del Washington Memorial, legandolo fisicamente e storicamente al sito
.
.

Posted @withrepost • @princetonu_artmuseum Join us this Tuesday 11/5 at 5pm to hear Maya Lin in conversation with Museum Director James Steward.

Marking the completion of two new signature works of public art at Princeton by the world-renowned artist Maya Lin, this informal discussion will focus on public art, design inspiration, and the relationship in Lin’s practice between art, architecture, and design. The two new major commissions are The Princeton Line, an undulating sculpted line of molded earth that travels a steep slope, and Einstein’s Table, a granite “water table,” both important additions to the University’s public art collection, which is already deemed to be among the finest in the nation.

This event is free and open to the public and take place on stage in Richardson Auditorium. Reserve tickets through tickets.princeton.edu or call 609-258-9220. Tickets will also be available at the door until 4:50 pm and while supplies last. A reception in the Museum will follow.

Congratulations to Maya Lin, who will be honored this Saturday, July 13 at the Parrish Art Museum's (@parrishart) 2019 Midsummer Party in Water Mill, New York! On view in a special exhibition commemorating the event is Lin's 2014 work "Bay, Pond, & Harbor (Long Island Triptych)," pictured here.
-
The winner of the 2009 National Medal of Arts and a 2016 recipient of the Presidential Medal of Freedom, #MayaLin’s acclaimed work encompasses large-scale environmental installations, intimate studio artworks, architectural projects, and memorials. In her sculpture and drawing, Lin interprets the world through a twenty-first century lens, utilizing technological methods to study and visualize the natural environment. Blurring boundaries between two- and three-dimensional space, Lin sets up a systematic ordering of the landscape tied to history, time, science, and language.
-

The Obert C. and Grace A. Tanner Humanities Center at the University of Utah presents the 2019 Tanner Lecture on Human Values given by artist and designer, Maya Lin, Wednesday, Nov. 20, 7 p.m. at Kingsbury Hall. Lin interprets the natural world through history, politics and culture, creating a body of work that balances art and architecture. 
In her presentation, “At the Intersection of Art and Architecture,” Lin will discuss her work and how her pursuit of both art and architecture has impacted her design process. A daughter of immigrants, Lin has forged a rare path that includes seminal art, architectural works as well as groundbreaking memorials.

A Fold in the Field, Maya Lin, Gibbs Farm, Makarau, New Zealand, 2013
.
Encompassing approximately 30,000 square metres, “A Fold in the Field” is Maya Lin’s largest and most ambitious #earthwork to date. It is Lin’s first earthwork depicting folds in the #earth of which there are five in total, the highest of which gently rises to 11.5 metres. Set on a flat plain, the folds emerge and billow from the terrain, the slopes determined with The Farms wildlife in mind, permitting the sheep to graze the slopes and keep the #grass the appropriate length. This is consistent with her large-scale environmental artworks, and the artist’s interest in how one experiences and relates to the #landscape. Lin’s five folds make dramatic new wave forms in the flattest and lowest section of the Farm: the coastal flats
.
.
Con una superficie di circa 30.000 metri quadrati, "A Fold in the Field" è la più grande e ambiziosa opera di landart di Maya Lin fino ad oggi. È la prima opera di Lin che descrive le pieghe nella terra, ne sono presenti cinque in totale, la più alta delle quali sale dolcemente a 11,5 metri. Situate su una pianura piatta, le pieghe emergono e ondeggiano dal terreno, le pendenze studiate secondo la fauna selvatica di The Farms, permettendo alla pecora di pascolare le pendici e mantenere l'erba della lunghezza appropriata. Questo è coerente con le sue opere d'arte ambientale su larga scala e l'interesse dell'artista per come si vive e ci si relaziona con il #paesaggio. Le cinque pieghe di Lin creano forme drammatiche ondulate nella parte più piatta e bassa della fattoria: la pianura costiera
.
.

Maya Lin is probably most well know for her work in Washington, DC, the Vietnam War Memorial. She was just 21 when her design was chosen for the Vietnam War Memorial through a contest. Maya Lin was born in Athens, Ohio. Her work can be seen all over the country including the campus of Ohio State and right here in Cleveland!

If you have ever been downtown to the Cleveland Public Library and ventured into the Linda Eastman Reading Garden you may have noticed Maya's fountain. It is a gentle flowing fountain made up of granite paving blocks with a poem inscribed on it. The reading garden was redesigned and dedicated in 1998, after the Louis Stokes wing of the library was added.

The reading garden is a peaceful place right in the middle of the hustle and bustle of downtown Cleveland. Totally worth a stop or a sit!

⁣⁣
What is the most significant image you made in the last twelve months?⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Tag #thebeautifulreal_reflect and include in your caption an explanation of the significance. Perhaps it marked a life milestone. Or got published. Or sparked a ginormous client order. Or helped someone heal. Or is the first image you made for yourself in too long. Or won an award. Or absolutely, positively failed - the byproduct of a seemingly brilliant idea poorly executed (I made quite a few of these this year) - but which moved your work forward! Or something else entirely. You tell us.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
For a little kicker this week, between now and next Saturday 3 shares from #thebeautifulreal_reflect will be selected to receive an archival pigment print of their most significant image. For you to do with as you please - frame and hang at home, gift, tape to the ceiling above your bed so it haunts you when you fall asleep/wake-up, or use to hone your dart game. Whatever works for you.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Dig deep. Let's see what you've got.⁣⁣

A inicios de los 80 una joven estudiante de arquitectura, de sus cursos finales, presentó una sintética, abstracta y sutil propuesta para un concurso que buscaba erigir un monumento a los Veteranos de la guerra de Vietnam. La guerra fue uno de los momentos más oscuros y críticos de los 60 en Estados Unidos. El recuerdo, vivo, tangible, dramático, en un momento donde el entusiasmo por las reformas económicas de Reagan iban a dirigir el gigante del norte a una atalaya de desarrollo. Entre medio de todo esto, esta joven estudiante de arquitectura, con una escueta imagen pastoril y sublime a la vez cautivó a los jueves para volver Vietnam en una experiencia de muerte y vida en los visitantes, un contraste entre lo que al nivel de la calle era una realidad y bajo tierra, en una profunda opacidad de la piedra pulida era pura frontalidad. La arquitecta se llama Maya Lin y su environment "Vietnam Veterans Memorial". El campo que alteró para siempre sería el de los monumentos conmemorativos tan dados a abrazar el poder y su imagen canónica. En su reemplazo propuso los memoriales, espacios, entornos, que buscaban generar emotividad y afección en los visitantes, no la unicidad del rostro y sus atributos. Con eso cambió el paisaje del #publicart para siempre. Por estos días se habla de un profundo cuestionamiento de los monumentos @andres_duran_d que los vuelve dúctiles a la calle y reactivos al mensaje, utilitarios para la fotogenia, pero esteriles en su significancia. Cómo recordaremos este momento histórico iniciado el 18 de octubre? Cómo recordaremos el proceso de #nuevaconstitucion ? Será visto con esperanza? Se transmitirá la imagen de un nuevo Chile o bien caeremos en los vicios de su versión 1.0? #mayalin #memorials pd: qué registro fotográfico más vivo.

In 1981, Maya Lin, a 21 year old architecture student at Yale University, beat out over 1,400 competitors in a competition to design the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. Although she proposed an apolitical monument, the design proved controversial. Veterans groups criticized her design and complained that it seemingly honored only the fallen and not the living veterans. Lin defended her design in front of the US Congress, and eventually, a compromise was reached. Lin's work has shaped our public consciousness and given women like us inspiration to change the world. #architectureofwomen #mayalin

At the age of just 21 and while she was still finishing her undergraduate degree at Yale, Maya Lin (born October 5, 1959) won the design competition for the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington DC. The memorial went on to become among the most recognizable designs in the world, and heralded a sea change for memorial design, breaking with classical conventions and dramatically changing the discourse of a typology.

Sneak 👀! @colbymuseum interns helped install 'Interrupted River: Penobscot' this month, a @mayalinstudio piece that features in our upcoming exhibition 'Occupy Colby: Artists Need to Create on the Same Scale That Society Has the Capacity to Destroy, Year 2.'
-
Occupy Colby is part of the ongoing exhibition initiated by the @brooklynrail  in 2017 at Mana Contemporary, Jersey City. The exhibition featured artists whose works invoke contemporary political and social issues such as human rights and equality, immigration, international relations, and the environment. This second iteration of the project focuses solely on environmental issues and particularly on climate change—perhaps now the most pressing of humanity’s concerns. Participating artists also include Lauren Bon, Mel Chin, Justin Brice Guariglia, and Meg Webster.
-
At the Colby Museum, Rail Curatorial Projects will work with the Lunder Institute for American Art to engage faculty, students, and Waterville residents in a series of cross-disciplinary responses to the work in the exhibition. Public programming will include panel discussions, poetry readings, and dance and musical performances. The Brooklyn Rail, in collaboration with the Colby Museum and the Lunder Institute for American Art, will also produce and publish a special autumn 2019 issue in connection with the exhibition.

Unexpected Connection.  Vietnam War Memorial.  Washington DC (2019)
.
Much respect and kindest regards to anyone who made the ultimate sacrifice, and to those surviving the pain of loss...
.
For my 200th IG post, I had envisioned some epic photo from some epic place.  I still have a few.  Memorial Day made this more appropriate.  Cold and threat of rain contributed to the sadness of this moment.  Yes, I had visualized catching a photo like this.  But I wasn’t prepared for The Girl’s connection. Maya Lin is her favorite architect.  She has a favorite architect!  Who knows if she fully absorbed the gravity and meaning of this hallowed ground.  But I do feel that she had an intuitive response, and understood the sadness of this place.  She felt a need to re-stand each flower that had fallen over.  Let me say, I’ve been here three times now and I’ve seen it through misty eyes each time. This is the first time I’ve seen it through a photographer’s lens. Photography is more difficult when you’re fighting back tears.
.

10 years ago I travelled to the Pacific Northwest (USA) in search of a farsighted art project designed to connect Native American, European and Scientific communities. Led by architect Maya Lin and a super passionate not-for-project organisation, @confluencenw now sits as a series of six timeless (& functional) artworks dotted along the Columbia River. They range from a stunning polished basalt fish-cleaning table to an epic wildlife/pedestrian bridge (pictured). As a landscape architecture graduate, originally my interest was in the role of design to create cross-cultural and ecological awareness. Inspired by Australian Aboriginal songlines I saw this as a contemporary co-dreaming trail, a healing project that could unite people through a common care for their environment. In this case, a river system. There's more work to do. The final and seventh site at Celilo Falls, where traditional fishing runs have fallen silent due to damming, remains the greatest place of hurt.

The project team is focusing their energy on a school education program called 'Confluence in the Classroom'. Conceived by Warm Springs Elder and Artist Lillian Pitt, the learning experience gives young people a direct relationship to precious 'culture bearers' and the opportunity to see the world through Indigenous eyes. Last year the program connected around 12 Native American artists with over 1000 school children.

From that point of view, the biggest legacy of Confluence is filling a gap in Indigenous history and living culture within the education system. Donors from the community have said, this is important and they're not getting this exposure elsewhere, until now. In 2017, the Oregon legislature enacted Senate Bill 13 'Tribal History/Shared History' which requires the state's Department of Education to create K - 12 Native American curriculum. With this new mainstream vehicle, all the hard work is set to pay off. 
Art & community laid foundations for a world class Indigenous education experience that could be modelled by schools around the globe. Change is in motion.

Ps: Parents, teachers, Confluence's website/online library is a great reference if you're looking where to begin.

Join us this Tuesday 11/5 at 5pm to hear Maya Lin in conversation with Museum Director James Steward.

Marking the completion of two new signature works of public art at Princeton by the world-renowned artist Maya Lin, this informal discussion will focus on public art, design inspiration, and the relationship in Lin’s practice between art, architecture, and design. The two new major commissions are The Princeton Line, an undulating sculpted line of molded earth that travels a steep slope, and Einstein’s Table, a granite “water table,” both important additions to the University’s public art collection, which is already deemed to be among the finest in the nation.

This event is free and open to the public and will take place on stage in Richardson Auditorium. Reserve tickets through tickets.princeton.edu or call 609-258-9220. Tickets will also be available at the door until 4:50 pm and while supplies last. A reception in the Museum will follow.

Had to make a detour due to constructions downtown and came a cross this!! Maya Lin’s Sounding Stones. Beautiful. Sound on..
Maya Lin's Sounding Stones was installed outside the Federal Courthouse Plaza in 1996. Consisting of four sequentially placed granite blocks, each cut through to create viewing holes to see neighboring blocks or to see and hear water fountains contained within the blocks, they mark the pedestrians' path between the path between the Worth and Earl Street entrances to the Federal Building. Each stone averages six feet square, but varies in separation between blocks.

Maya Ying Lin (5 Oct. 1959- ) Chinese-American designer, architect and artist who works in sculpture and land art
.
پدر و مادر لین از چینی‌های مهاجر بودند. درسال ۱۹۸۱ هنگامی که دانشگاه ییل تحصیل می‌کرد، در مسابقه‌ی طراحی "بنای یادبود سربازان جنگ ویتنام" برنده شد؛ دیوارهای ساده با سنگ گرانیت سیاه که هزاران نام بر آن‌ها حک شده‌اند (تصویر نخست و دوم). در این اثر، بازتاب تصویر بازماندگان بر دیوار مملو از نام‌های ازدست‌رفتگان‌ جنگ، رابطه‌ی معناداری میان دنیای زندگان و مردگان ایجاد کرده است. لین بعدن با شباهت‌هایی "بنای یادبود حقوق مدنی‌" را در سال ۱۹۸۹ در آلاباما ساخت (تصویر سوم). .
لین همچنین در عرصه‌های مختلف، از مجسمه‌سازی و نقاشی تا طراحی فضای داخلی، طراحی اثاثیه خانگی، آثار چیدمانی و یادمان‌ها کار کرده است. .
چشم‌اندازها و تاکید لین همواره بر چگونگی فضا در آینده و تعادل و ارتباطش با طبیعت و آن‌چه برای مردم معنا دارد، بوده است. او تلاش کرده به تاثیر سیاست بر طراحی کمتر توجه کند تا آن‌چه احساسات در فضا خلق کرده و برای مخاطب نمادسازی می‌کند. لین از دوران جوانی و دانشجویی در فعالیت‌های‌ زیست‌محیطی مشارکت داشته و در هنر زمینی (land art) نیز تجارب موفقی داشته است.

As with all the RA Editions programme, sales of works generate valuable revenue for the RA and in particular the RA Schools - supporting artists and supporting our environment: couldn’t be better!!! More on Maya Lin, who created the women’s table at Yale.
#RP @lizlangley Maya Lin, sculptor, architect and landscape artist. At age 21, she won a competition to design the Vietnam War Memorial. Her pared down, non- traditional design was controversial at the time, but it's now visited by 10,000 people each day. This also marked the start of a flourishing career. She went on to design a memorial to the civil rights movement & many other landscape installations and buildings. She's known for incorporating nature into her designs and creating spaces that interact with the inhabitant on a personal level.

Ellen S. Clark Hope Plaza, Maya Lin, Washington University School of Medicine, Saint Louis, #Missouri, #USA, 2010
.
From the designer words: I wanted to create the effect of floating, surrounded by a #pool of water lilies. I utilized a significant grade change from one side of the pool to the opposite side to create a #circular body of water that you could step onto at grade. As one walks around the pool, the pool transforms into a cantilevered bowl with #water lilies floating in it. The plaza is part of the BJC Institute of Health at Washington University School of Medicine, where people who need to visit have some of the toughest and most untreatable diseases. I wanted to create a #quiet, #peaceful refuge with a simple bowl of #flowers surrounding them. The quote that is cut into the inner circle is from Emily Dickinson's poem "Hope"
.
.
Dalle parole della designer: volevo creare l'effetto del galleggiamento, circondato da una pozza di #ninfee. Ho utilizzato un cambio di grado significativo da un lato della piscina al lato opposto per creare un corpo d'acqua circolare calpestabile. Mentre si cammina intorno alla piscina, questa si trasforma in una ciotola a sbalzo con ninfee galleggianti. La piazza fa parte del BJC Institute of Health della Washington University School of Medicine, dove i pazienti hanno alcune delle malattie più difficili e più incurabili. Volevo creare un rifugio tranquillo e pacifico con una semplice ciotola di #fiori che lo circondi. La citazione incisa nel cerchio interno è tratta dal poema "Speranza" di Emily Dickinson
.

The Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C. was dedicated on November 13, 1982 to honor the service members who had lost their lives during this controversial war. A site near the Lincoln Memorial was chosen and authorized by Congress and a design competition was announced. Maya Lin, a 21-year-old architecture student at Yale, won the blind competition. The artist and her minimalist design drew criticism: some detractors protested her Asian heritage, while others disliked the idea of the black granite monument with no ornamentation. Lin’s idea was to create a symbolic open wound in the earth to replicate the grief over those who were lost. The finished memorial proved to be an immersive experience, as the names of the dead rise higher and higher the closer the visitor gets to the center of the memorial; at the same time, the shiny granite acts like a mirror, reflecting the faces of the living. This powerful combination, as well as the 58,320 names chiseled into the granite, inspired pilgrimages by Vietnam veterans and their families. Thousands of objects, including flowers, notes, dog tags, army boots, and other memorabilia have been left in tribute at what has come to be known fondly as “the wall.” *

A little strange to say this is something we’re looking forward to, but so it goes: artist and architect @mayalinstudio will be placing a grove of spectral cedar trees within New York’s @madsqparknyc next June; it’s part of her forthcoming summer 2020 installation focusing on how climate change has impacted forests around the world.

Lin has arranged to source these dead trees (Atlantic Cedars) from the Pine Barrens in New Jersey, which was significantly damaged by extreme salinization during Hurricane Sandy in 2012. Entitled Ghost Forest, the show draws its name from woodlands like the Pine Barrens that have died due to climate change, sea-level rise, and saltwater infiltration. #MayaLin is an architect, sculptor, and artist whose artwork will be celebrated in @cbryanmusic's "Syzygy", set to premiere at Sight + Sound on March 7 & 9. The artwork shown is a combination of two of Lin's works. The hanging 3-d wire line-drawing is called "Water Line", and represents a scale map of the Mid Atlantic Ridge ocean floor. On the ground, "Blue Lake Pass" embodies the Rocky Mountains of Colorado, which are segmented and pulled apart so people can walk through. This represents how natural terrain is often systematized by people, and exemplifies Lin's passion for nature.

Can you name 5 women artists? Most people the National Museum of Women in the Arts spoke to for a recent Women’s History Month campaign couldn’t.  Not in my house!  I like to read books about artists with my kids like *Women Artists A to Z" by Melanie LaBarge, illustrated by Caroline Corrigan.  This book highlights both the well-known favorite female artists (of course Frida Kahlo and Georgia O'Keeffe) as well as interesting and diverse choices beyond like Bette Saar, Elizabeth Catlett, and Carmen Herrera.  It is a great intro for young and old readers alike as it is not too wordy (though it has further info in the back if you want to dig deeper) and the vivid illustrations are a delight and honor each artist's style.  Stay tuned to @picturebookny this month (and ok, every month) for more features on books on great female artists. Link in profile to purchase.

This memorial day we are celebrating the work of Maya Lin, the Chinese-American architect behind the design of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, one of the most visited memorials in the US. She is also the inspiration behind our 'Stone Stories' necktie. ☺️ Her design was just the beginning though as additional memorials followed just feet from hers.
.
Maya Lin was only 21 years old and a senior at Yale when her anonymous design was selected, but its sleek black granite wall was immediately met with controversy as people claimed it was not representative of America or their efforts in the war. The design however stayed intact and was unveiled Nov. 1982.
.
The same year, the Vietnam Veterans Memorial Fund commissioned Frederick Hart to create a sculpture for their monument. Two years later, the bronze Three Soldiers statue was unveiled just a few feet from the Vietnam Veterans Memorial wall. Tough to argue that the statue wasn’t added to offer an alternative for critics of Maya’s design…
.
But between these two memorials, only 8 women are represented by way of their names being etched on the wall. It has been reported that anywhere between 7,500 to 11,000 women served in the Vietnam War, with others claiming tens of thousands more as civilian women became more involved in the war. .
Enter Diane Carlson Evans, a former Army nurse who led a campaign to get a memorial representative of the women that served in Vietnam. Her campaign was largely met with “leave enough alone”, but eventually, in 1993, the Vietnam Women’s Memorial, sculpted by Glenna Goodacre, was unveiled 60 feet from the other memorials. The Vietnam Women’s Memorial Foundation lists 67 American women - 8 military and 59 civilians gave their lives in the war. Swipe to see the three memorials.

Maya Lin’s creativity was encouraged in her childhood, by the example of her parents. Maya made art inspired by her mother’s poetry and visited her father’s ceramic’s studio every day.  She liked to stay home to study or make things. She crafted with any materials she could find: string, paper, silver scraps and more, exorcising her imagination to seek fresh perspectives. She followed her creative path, always seeking balance, to great and continued success as an adult.

#cross contour line in #3D form #blue lake pass #2006 #Duraflake Particleboard by #Maya Lin #mayalin.  Blue Lake Pass is a landmark in the Rocky Mountains near where the artist has a summer home. Using cut particleboard, a common construction material, Lin created a topographical landscape of the pass. She gridded its terrain into 3-foot square sections, and then pulled the distinct sections apart, allowing visitors to walk narrow pathways through the landscape. “ I wanted to shift one’s perspective about the land, allowing a viewpoint that is more geological in character”

Next up, we have another Novartis building, Novartis BioMedical Research Institutes, 181 Mass Ave, that has been nominated for the 2019 Harleston Parker Medal. This building was designed by Maya Lin with Bialosky + Partners Architects and CannonDesign.
•
Lin writes of the building’s design, “I wanted to create a campuslike character for the Novartis community with this design. I envisioned a courtyard green-space within the compound's interior as a counterpoint to the hard-scaped plaza of Novartis's existing buildings directly across the street, as well as a garden for both Novartis's employees and the public.”
•
Of the unique facade, Lin writes, “The design of the stone facade is inspired by microscopic views of organic coral or bone structure. Conceptually I felt this translation of nature through a systematic and mathematical process reflects back on how science and medicine take materials found in nature and, through scientific analysis and research, transform them into new medicinal compounds.” 📷 @terrificshots
•

Ellen S. Clark Hope Plaza, Maya Lin, Washington University School of Medicine, Saint Louis, #Missouri, #USA, 2010
.
From the designer words: I wanted to create the effect of floating, surrounded by a #pool of water lilies. I utilized a significant grade change from one side of the pool to the opposite side to create a #circular body of water that you could step onto at grade. As one walks around the pool, the pool transforms into a cantilevered bowl with #water lilies floating in it. The plaza is part of the BJC Institute of Health at Washington University School of Medicine, where people who need to visit have some of the toughest and most untreatable diseases. I wanted to create a #quiet, #peaceful refuge with a simple bowl of #flowers surrounding them. The quote that is cut into the inner circle is from Emily Dickinson's poem "Hope"
.
.
Dalle parole della designer: volevo creare l'effetto del galleggiamento, circondato da una pozza di #ninfee. Ho utilizzato un cambio di grado significativo da un lato della piscina al lato opposto per creare un corpo d'acqua circolare calpestabile. Mentre si cammina intorno alla piscina, questa si trasforma in una ciotola a sbalzo con ninfee galleggianti. La piazza fa parte del BJC Institute of Health della Washington University School of Medicine, dove i pazienti hanno alcune delle malattie più difficili e più incurabili. Volevo creare un rifugio tranquillo e pacifico con una semplice ciotola di #fiori che lo circondi. La citazione incisa nel cerchio interno è tratta dal poema "Speranza" di Emily Dickinson
.
.

Maya Lin (b.1959) is an American designer and artist who works primarily in sculpture and land art to address historical moments and environmental issues. Using technology like sonar maps and satellite imaging, Lin’s acute installations explore the relationship people have with their environment by bringing elements of nature into an urban setting. For example, in “Water Line” (2006) Lin used wire to reconstruct the topography of the Mid-Atlantic Ridge, which is the ocean floor north of Antarctica and one of the most remote places on earth. Bringing the contours of the bottom of the sea to an interior gallery space is indicative of Lin’s astounding ability to synthesize momentous nature into an accessible viewing experience. Lin’s most famous installation is the Vietnam Veterans Memorial (1981), which consists of two long mirrors with the names of fallen soldiers engraved on its surface. "I'm very much a product of the growing awareness about ecology and the environment movement," Lin explains. "I am very drawn to landscape, and my work is about finding a balance in the landscape, respecting nature not trying to dominate it. Even the Vietnam Veterans Memorial is an earthwork. All of my work is about slipping things in, inserting an order or a structuring, yet making an interface so that in the end, rather than a hierarchy, there is a balance and tension between the man-made and the natural."
.

#mayalin is an American designer, architect, and artist who works in sculpture and land art. She achieved national recognition at the age of 21 while still an undergraduate at Yale University, when her design for the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C. was chosen in a national competition. It is considered one of the most influential memorials of the post-World War II period.

Lin has designed other memorials and numerous public and private buildings, landscape design, and sculpture. Although Lin's best known sculptures and architectural work are historical memorials, she also honors nature through her environmentally themed works. In creating works which deal with the environment in decline, Lin aims to raise awareness for the environment for audiences in urban spaces. Lin has stated that environmental issues have concerned her since she was very young, and she dedicated much of her time at Yale University to environmental activism.[10] Her interest in the environment stems from her upbringing in rural Ohio. The Hopewell and Adena Indian burial mounds inspired Lin from an early age. Much of her later work, after her work on memorials, focuses on the relationship that people have with their environment, which she displays in earthworks, sculptures, and installations. "I'm very much a product of the growing awareness about ecology and the environment al movement," Lin says. "I am very drawn to landscape, and my work is about finding a balance in the landscape, respecting nature not trying to dominate it. Even the Vietnam Veterans Memorial is an earthwork. All of my work is about slipping things in, inserting an order or a structuring, yet making an interface so that in the end, rather than a hierarchy, there is a balance and tension between the man-made and the natural." Lin's work centers on the concept of uncovering "hidden histories" to bring attention to landscapes and environments that may otherwise be inaccessible to viewers and "deploys the concept to discuss the inextricable relationship between nature and the built environment." "I am very drawn to landscape, and my work is about finding a balance in the landscape, respecting nature not trying to dominate it."—Maya Lin⁠⠀
⁠⠀
Although most well known for her design of The Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C., much of Maya Lin's more contemporary work focuses on sculptural and land art as well as architecture—inspired often by the natural features and landscape of the Earth.⁠⠀
⁠⠀
Her sculptural lines interact not only with the viewer, but also with the environment they are a part of—they shift over time, the soil erodes and washes away—as the force of nature plays its part and fuses the art with its landscape.⁠⠀

I have never seen this mocha color all over on a cat... and her eyes, if you could see in person, are literally patches of blue, green, gold, and gray with brown specks. She is intelligent, observant, spunky, and snuggly... and we are already so in love and so so glad she picked us to bring her home. ~It has been a year since we lost our Benjamin, so it has not been a decision we have made lightly. #architect #poet & writer #Linhuiyin was born on June 10, 1904. The first modern Chinese #femalearchitect, she and her husband founded the field of Chinese historical architecture. Her niece, the architect and artist #MayaLin, best known for designing the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, told Smithsonian Magazine in 2017 that “most people in China know more about Liang and Lin’s personalities and love lives than their work...But from an architectural point of view, they are hugely important...If it weren’t for them, we would have no record of so many ancient Chinese styles, which simply disappeared.” They tirelessly tracked across rural China recording and attempting to preserve historical buildings. Their notes and photos are often all that’s left of many of the buildings. #womenmakinghistory #herstory #womeninarchitecture #womenwholead #shero #chinesehistory #林徽因 #womenshistory #historicpreservation #watercolorillustration #womencreatingchange #feministart #chinesepoet #womenwhowrite #womenwhowritepoetry

Posted @withrepost • @pacegallery Congratulations to Maya Lin, who will be honored this Saturday, July 13 at the Parrish Art Museum's (@parrishart) 2019 Midsummer Party in Water Mill, New York! On view in a special exhibition commemorating the event is Lin's 2014 work "Bay, Pond, & Harbor (Long Island Triptych)," pictured here.
-
The winner of the 2009 National Medal of Arts and a 2016 recipient of the Presidential Medal of Freedom, #MayaLin’s acclaimed work encompasses large-scale environmental installations, intimate studio artworks, architectural projects, and memorials. In her sculpture and drawing, Lin interprets the world through a twenty-first century lens, utilizing technological methods to study and visualize the natural environment. Blurring boundaries between two- and three-dimensional space, Lin sets up a systematic ordering of the landscape tied to history, time, science, and language.

The remarkable 500 acre Storm King Art Center is an outdoor museum located in the Hudson Valley just over an hour from New York City.
.
I haven’t visited in more than two decades - there have been many outstanding additions to the collection of outdoor sculptures and earthworks - there are now more than 100 works in the permanent collection!
.
Visitors can stroll the extensive roadways and trails, rent bikes or take the free trolley. There are places to picnic and a number of food vendors to purchase snacks or meals. I recommend getting there early - they open at 10 am, or go later in the afternoon when the light enhances the installations - open until 8pm.
.

Join us in the Main Gallery this evening (Thursday, June 13) for our final 'Continuum' exhibition program, a presentation of MAYA LIN: A STRONG CLEAR VISION.
.
This documentary reveals the contentious origins of the Vietnam Veterans Memorial and tells the story of its creator, a 21-year-old architecture student whose plan was selected from over 1,000 different designs, beating out some of the most prestigious architecture firms from around the world.
.
Renowned filmmaker Freida Lee Mock combines interviews and archival footage to chronicle Lin’s story — from its origins, dominated by her David vs. Goliath battle over the Vietnam Veterans Memorial, to a career designing other memorials, always with an innate talent and resolute courage.
.
This event is held as part of a full schedule of related programming for the exhibition 'Continuum: 1808 to 2017 / Goya to Erdreich,' which takes an unflinching look at the effects of war and other atrocities on society.

From the moment a camera was set into my hands in highschool, a duct-taped Canon 35mm from the days before the invention of digital, I've turned my lens toward the spectators and participants as often as to the event. A school football game is about the players on the field, but it's also about the Waterboys, the spirit team, the band, the community cheering on their Alma mater. Turning towards the stands while on the field and plays are being made isn't the best idea, though. 🙄

An art museum or a nature trail is the same way.  These things have intrinsic value, but the people who enjoy them are intrinsic to the being and value of these spaces. Seeing how other people and spaces interact (or don't) in a space is as interesting as one's own reactions. At least, to this artist.

Today we’re highlighting Maya Lin, an American artist, architect, and environmentalist. Maya first stunned the world at 21 years old, when she anonymously won a nationwide Vietnam Veterans Memorial design competition while she was still a student at Yale. Like issue eight’s featured role model, architect Zaha Hadid, Maya inspires us to think innovatively!⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
The daughter of Chinese immigrants, Maya was born and raised in Athens, Ohio. Her parents, who were professors at Ohio University, focused on academics and the arts. Maya loved studying, got straight A’s, and took courses at the university for fun. Her parents encouraged her to make art—so when Maya wasn’t studying, she was casting bronze at the university’s foundry.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Maya studied architecture because it combined her passion for art, math, and science. In 1981, after she won the Vietnam Veterans Memorial competition, Maya faced harsh criticism by government officials, including President Ronald Reagan. At the time, her minimalist design went against traditional memorial architecture, so critics wanted to alter it. But Maya didn’t cave in and even defended her work at a Senate hearing. But she prevailed and became the first woman to design a memorial on the U.S.’s National Mall.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Since then, Maya’s been unstoppable! She’s designed large-scale environmental pieces, buildings, and monuments. Through her work, she educates viewers on different issues—from social injustice to nature conservation. Some of her designs include the Civil Rights Memorial in Alabama, Yale’s “The Woman’s Table” sculpture, and “What Is Missing?”, a project about extinct species and climate change. President Barack Obama awarded her with the National Medal of Arts and the Presidential Medal of Freedom for her work.⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
In Maya’s own words, “to fly we have to have resistance.” Maya’s groundbreaking career is proof of what happens when we question tradition and persevere in the face of skeptics. 📷: WSJ #mayalin #bravewomanhighlight

#mayalin #stormkingwavefield #stormkingartcenter #americaineartiste #femmeartiste #feminisme #landart #paysage #environement #artcontemporaine Champ d’’ondes de la tempête est un chef-d’œuvre de 240.000 pieds carrés, à la Storm King Art Foundation. Vue de haut, les houles ondulantes de la terre formant le champ d’ondes semblent s’élever naturellement du terrain herbeux et rouler le long de celui-ci. Sur une toile de fond formée par le mont Schunnemunk à l’ouest et les hautes terres de l’Hudson au sud et à l’est, le terrassement de Maya inspire une large perspective sur le paysage d’où il émerge et incite à une exploration profonde des allées herbeuses entre les cimes. Les sept vagues de près de quatre cents pieds de long, dont la hauteur varie de dix à quinze pieds, se déroulent à la même échelle qu’une série de vagues médio-océaniques. L’effet qui en résulte rappelle l’expérience d’être en mer , où la vue des vagues adjacentes et de la terre est perdue entre les houles. Lin a choisi le site de onze acres comme projet de remise en état de l’environnement, un remaniement durable de l’ancienne gravière qui a fourni les matériaux pour la voie de passage de l’État de New York. « J’ai eu tendance à créer des œuvres sur les bords et les limites des lieux. J’ai toujours su que je voulais culminer la série avec un champ qui littéralement, quand on y était, on s’y perdait » Lin a collaboré avec des architectes paysagistes pour utiliser le gravier et la terrre végétale existants sur le site. Les graminées à faible impact et le système de drainage naturel qu’elle a mis en place font de Wavefield une œuvre organique et vivante qui continue d’évoluer.

Back to celebrating amazing Asian role models. If you want to see the previous 32 role models, check out my official page for @dimsum_love .
No. 33 is Maya Lin who was the first female architect to have designed a monument on our National Mall. The Vietnam War Memorial is a living tribute to the lives that we lost and has created a place of healing for a very questionable era of our nation’s history. On a personal account, my father was an architect and steered me from being one, even though I had shown early interest in it. His main reason was that he didn’t want to see his little girl pay the rough dues in a predominantly male profession at the time. Ironically, one of my father’s Harvard GSD classmate, King-Lui Wu had taught Lin. That realization debunked that myth quickly for me. In the end, we are all meant to be on our perfect and imperfect paths.

I repost this image I shot in Washington DC years ago because it is so evocative of today’s holiday. 
We remember today the men and women who gave the ultimate sacrifice for us and our country. Their sense of duty - stronger than their sense of self.
As of May, 2018, there are 58,320 names - including eight women.
The high shine of the memorial is to capture our reflections, bringing the past and present together.

The names inscribed are not a complete list of those who are eligible for inclusion as some names were omitted at the request of families.
Those who are declared dead are denoted by a diamond, and those who are status unknown are denoted with a cross. When the death of one who was previously missing is confirmed, a diamond is superimposed over the cross. If the missing were to return alive, which has never occurred to date, the cross is to be circumscribed by a circle.
The walls are sunken into the ground, with the earth behind them. At the highest tip (the apex where they meet), they are 10.1 feet (3.1 m) high, and they taper to a height of 8 inches (200 mm) at their extremities. Symbolically, this is described as a "wound that is closed and healing".
Stone for the wall came from Bangalore, Karnataka, India. It was chosen because of its reflective quality and also because of opposition to Swedish and Canadian stone, as those countries were destinations for draft evaders. One wall points toward the Washington Monument, the other in the direction of the Lincoln Memorial, meeting at an angle of 125° 12′. Each wall has 72 panels, 70 listing names (numbered 1E through 70E and 70W through 1W) and two very small blank panels at the extremities.

Without them, I cannot imagine where our country would be today.

Posted @phillydesign.win Posted @withrepost • @princetonu_artmuseum Join us this Tuesday 11/5 at 5pm to hear Maya Lin in conversation with Museum Director James Steward.

Marking the completion of two new signature works of public art at Princeton by the world-renowned artist Maya Lin, this informal discussion will focus on public art, design inspiration, and the relationship in Lin’s practice between art, architecture, and design. The two new major commissions are The Princeton Line, an undulating sculpted line of molded earth that travels a steep slope, and Einstein’s Table, a granite “water table,” both important additions to the University’s public art collection, which is already deemed to be among the finest in the nation.

This event is free and open to the public and take place on stage in Richardson Auditorium. Reserve tickets through tickets.princeton.edu or call 609-258-9220. Tickets will also be available at the door until 4:50 pm and while supplies last. A reception in the Museum will follow.

Ettore Sottsass - 6. As an architect’s son, who had studied architecture and started his career by working for his father, it’s easy to understand why Ettore Sottsass should have decided to explore other areas of design after opening his own studio in 1946. He took on occasional architectural projects over the next forty years, including a friend’s house in the Roman countryside in 1966, and a ceramics workshop in Tuscany three years later. But it was not the mid-1980s, when Sottsass left Memphis, that architecture became a focus of his work. One of his first projects was this, the Wolf House, designed in the late 1980s for the US photography dealer Daniel Wolf and his wife, the architect Maya Lin, near Mount Sneffels in Colorado. Stylistically, Sottsass’s architecture shared the bold contrasts of colours, shapes, materials and symbolism of his work in product design, and conceptually it was steeped in the same post-modernist sensibility. Yet each of his buildings, the houses especially, was designed “to be in", as he put it, because Sottsass orchestrated the experience of entering or leaving a room, and moving between them, so skilfully.

Did you know that Maya Lin was only 21 years old when she designed the memorial for the Vietnam War in Washington, D.C.? When asked what helped shape her design, Lin said “I though about what death is, what a loss is. A sharp pain that lessens with time, but can never quite heal over. A scar. The idea occurred to me there on the site. Take a knife and cut open the earth, and with time the grass would heal it. As if you cut open the rock and polished it.” Today we acknowledge and honor the sacrifice of so many and the grief and scars that their loved ones bear. 📸Peter Marlow/Magnum Photos

Three Legged Buddha (detail), 2007
Zhang Huan (b. 1965) @zhanghuanofficial

Zhang Huan is a contemporary Chinese artist based in Shanghai. He began his career as a painter, transitioned to performance art, then back to painting, while dabbling in several mediums like sculpture in between. The Three-Legged Buddha was his piece for the @stormkingartcenter. While the legs of the Three Legged Buddha are modeled closely after fragments of bronze Buddha sculptures Zhang encountered on a trip to Tibet in 2005, the sculpture’s face—visible only from the nostrils upward—is a self-portrait. Zhang folds his body into his art, much as he did in the 1990s, when he came to prominence for performance-based work. Zhang designed the hatches in the sculpture to provide access to the interior so that incense might be burned inside, with smoke emanating through holes in the Buddha’s toes, nostrils and eyes.

I kept this postcard because it was the best one at the Stormking Gift Shop of the Three Legged buddha. In the summer of 2018, I visited the sculpture park (as made famous on Master if None) with @anniesoud and @henrylmn. It was a beautiful day, and even among the Andy Goldsworthys and Maya Lins, the Three Legged Buddha’s was my favorite. It was the most human piece at Stormking—surreal, strange and thought-provoking.

🌿Геопластика – это формирование нового/преобразование существующего рельефа участка.

Геопластика может использоваться как в практических, так и в чисто эстетических целях. Это не только создание удобных для ландшафтных целей откосов и террас, но и, скажем, моделирование совершенно новых, не существовавших прежде холмов или создание заглубленных садовых амфитеатров.

Профессиональный ландшафтный архитектор работает по нормативам – именно они определяют угол откоса в зависимости от свойств грунта и практических задач, уклоны дорожек и лестниц.
⠀
Однако первое, что приходит в голову (и появляется в поисковике) при слове «геопластика» – это совершенно фантастические холмы Чарльза Дженкса или уходящие вдаль волны на поле в скульптурном парке StormKing.

A Fold in the Field, Maya Lin, Gibbs Farm, Makarau, New Zealand, 2013
.
Encompassing approximately 30,000 square metres, “A Fold in the Field” is Maya Lin’s largest and most ambitious #earthwork to date. It is Lin’s first earthwork depicting folds in the #earth of which there are five in total, the highest of which gently rises to 11.5 metres. Set on a flat plain, the folds emerge and billow from the terrain, the slopes determined with The Farms wildlife in mind, permitting the sheep to graze the slopes and keep the #grass the appropriate length. This is consistent with her large-scale environmental artworks, and the artist’s interest in how one experiences and relates to the #landscape. Lin’s five folds make dramatic new wave forms in the flattest and lowest section of the Farm: the coastal flats
.
.
Con una superficie di circa 30.000 metri quadrati, "A Fold in the Field" è la più grande e ambiziosa opera di landart di Maya Lin fino ad oggi. È la prima opera di Lin che descrive le pieghe nella terra, ne sono presenti cinque in totale, la più alta delle quali sale dolcemente a 11,5 metri. Situate su una pianura piatta, le pieghe emergono e ondeggiano dal terreno, le pendenze studiate secondo la fauna selvatica di The Farms, permettendo alla pecora di pascolare le pendici e mantenere l'erba della lunghezza appropriata. Questo è coerente con le sue opere d'arte ambientale su larga scala e l'interesse dell'artista per come si vive e ci si relaziona con il #paesaggio. Le cinque pieghe di Lin creano forme drammatiche ondulate nella parte più piatta e bassa della fattoria: la pianura costiera
.

Happy birthday, Maya Lin! 🎂 🎈🎉 Maya was 21 years old when she won the design competition for the Vietnam Veterans Memorial. She beat out more than 1,400 other entries. Her design, which was unique and untraditional, called for the memorial to made of polished granite. It would appear as a rift in the earth. The walls would be reflective so as to create a sense of personal reflection and private reckoning. She wanted people to be able to see themselves. The Wall would also be black - while everything else in Washington was white. To no surprise, this design caused controversy and uproar. Many derided it and she became a central part of the debate. Her design was called "the black gash of shame." Others didn't like that she was a woman, and some didn't like that she was of Chinese descent. Maya, who was born in Ohio, fought hard and pasionately for her design. She didn't back down, and through talks and debates, and an eventual compromise - she prevailed. Since 1982, her simplistic design has evoked a powerful sense of honor and reflection. She has gone on to have a rewarding and successful career. Maya was born #onthisday in 1959.
.

As a person with a cautious aversion to war memorials and monuments you would find me mostly straying away from these politically manipulated biases of memory.

Maya Lin's Vietnam veteran memorial is an exception.

A decade ago researching on it for a project, I was drawn to the empathetic and minimalist nature of her design and the subtle and powerful message it carried within but to have the opportunity to experience it was a whole different sensory journey (albeit a bit overloaded because of the crowds). Approaching the sunken black shard like wall emerging from the green lawn, one doesn't fully comprehend the scale of it all. Similar to how one approaches loss until you fully descend down the slope, until the names etched on the cool granite becomes visible to your naked eye. Inches away. Humans who lived. And at the apex, thousands of them. But now who exists only as a collection of letters. As you keep walking the names and the memories recess back to the soil and the ascending slope rejoins the elevation of the mall All along accompanied by your own reflection on the polished black wall. Making one reset on how we remember, how we view war and history, how we live with the wounds they inflict. And WHY we live.

_ “I imagined taking a knife and cutting into the earth, opening it up, an initial violence and pain that in time would heal.” - Maya Lin

Maya Lin, one of my artistic heroes, the sculptor most well-known for the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington D.C., has a work in New York's Penn Station, Eclipsed Time. Near the Long Island Railroad concourse. Most people even walk on top part of it on the floor below as they commute through the busy station every day. You have to look up in the ceiling to see the majority of the work. Now covered with construction apparatus and the wall text is nowhere to be found now. It is not currently working due to lighting issues. It was Installed back in 1994. A conceptual clock that tells time via the movement of light. Most people do not know we have such a work in NYC, our only Maya Lin that I know of. My wish is that they save the work as they renovate the train station. The next time you walk through Penn Station look up into the ceiling at the North east corner in the long corridor before you approach the red line (1,2,3) subway entrance.
.
.

Early morning run to Vietnam Veterans Memorial by land artist and architect Maya Lin.

In "Artists, Architects, Activists," @craigdykers, National Academician and Founding Partner of @snohetta, shares the people, places, and institutions that he finds inspiring. One such influence is the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington DC, designed by Maya Lin NA. Of the memorial and Lin's practice, Dykers says, "The design is a powerful reminder of grief, but also of hope and humanity. Lin herself is an inspiration; in her career she has managed to connect so many avenues of creative expression. She is successful as an artist, as well as an architect, and that is powerful.” See Dykers's complete list of inspirations at the link in our bio. ⁣

So what does Yerbba mean? 🤔
.
In archaic Spanish, yerba means grass. At Yerbba, we believe that medical information should be plentiful and accessible like hills of grass. Not just any grass: “good grass” or “yerba buena”. The Wave Field at University of Michigan is the perfect representation. Fun fact: it was built by the father of one of our team members!

Today, António Guterres (@antonioguterres), the Secretary-General of the @UnitedNations will meet with global leaders for the 2019 #ClimateActionSummit in New York, bringing together governments, the private sector, civil society, local authorities and other international organizations to develop concrete, realistic plans towards a stronger and healthier world. At #PaceGallery, we're grateful for the artists across the globe whose practices seek to inspire engagement, build awareness, and drive momentum for #ClimateAction, such as #MayaLin. Lin's work "Bay, Pond, & Harbor (Long Island Triptych)," from 2014, pictured here, is currently on view at the Parrish Art Museum (@parrishart) on the East End of Long Island, and calls attention to the local bioregion in which the museum is situated, depicting three landmark bodies of water, Mecox Bay, Georgica Pond, and Accabonac Harbor, in recycled silver.
-
A passionate advocate for the environment, Lin's work reveals aspects of the natural world that are normally invisible to us—the topography of the globe from ocean floor to mountain top, the evolving shape of coastlines and waterways—highlighting the need to consider how human activities impact the planet as a whole. In her own words: "On Long Island, you’re surrounded by water on both sides; you’ve got the bay coming up separating the North and the South Forks. I am extremely interested in the water’s edge, and thinking about sea level and understanding how transmutable and temporal that boundary between land and sea actually is. I’m very committed to doing something to help us understand and move quicker. I think this is going to be a huge part of our conversation in our lifetime. This is not something for the next two generations. It’s happening now.
-
Today, in support of @ART2030org and the @UnitedNations Climate Summit, we encourage you to share those artists who have inspired you to #ActNow in the fight against climate change.
-

#architectureofwomen Maya Lin's earthwork Eleven Minute Mile is another remarkable example of women shaping our world. EMM explores Lin's interest in the Native American burial and effigy mounds from her home state of Ohio. Among the largest and most striking of these mounds is the Serpent Mound of the Hopewell Indians (100 BC-700 AD). It's the source of inspiration for EMM, part drawing, part sculpture, which Lin describes as, "somewhere between a line and a walk." #mayalin

Fresh off his recent classroom visit, Executive Director of the Newport Restoration Foundation, Mark Thompson will be guiding a tour as part of the Preservation and Memory conference October 18-19.
.
Queen Anne Square is one of Newport's most creative and controversial examples of adaptive reuse. Maya Lin referenced the historic use of the property in her design for “The Meeting Room” at Queen Anne Square. This tour will discuss the design rationale and its connection to the site’s history while considering the degree to which the square serves to memorialize the past.
.

.
Founded in 1968, the Newport Restoration Foundation (NRF) is dedicated to promoting and investing in the architectural heritage of the Newport community, the traditional building trades, and Doris Duke's fine and decorative arts collection, for the enjoyment, education and inspiration of all. NRF also supports research and education in areas that relate directly to its collections and to issue of critical concern to the field of historic preservation.

#stormking 2/3 Maya Lin- Storm King Wave Field- 2007. I don’t know how I’ve missed this work every time I have visited since the install. It was featured in an article @abug shared and we HAD to spend some time here. Also- it’s right on a tram stop! (The park is 500 acres. This isn’t just me being lazy!) Now on view at the Grand Rapids Art Museum (@grartmuseum) is "Maya Lin: Flow," an exhibition of recent large-scale sculptures by renowned artist and designer #MayaLin. Created in recycled silver, steel pins, and common building materials, Lin conceived of each sculpture through the use of charting, mapping, and scientific research to determine each work’s ultimate design, layout, and structure.
-
Lin, a committed environmentalist, has created two new sculptures for the exhibition that focus directly on West Michigan. Through scope, scale, and the seeming use of abstraction, Lin expands our awareness of the Great Lakes and their connection to other bodies of water and to the geological forces that created them.
-

Vietnam Veterans Memorial, Maya Lin, #Washington D.C., #USA 1982
.
Two black #granite walls, placed below grade, engraved in chronological order with the names of the men and women who gave their lives in the Vietnam War. At the apex where the two walls meet, the dates 1959 and 1973 (marking the beginning and end of the #war) "meet" thus closing the circle of the time span of the war. A returning veteran can find his or her own time upon the wall, making each one's experience of the memorial very personal and individual. The siting of the piece is directly related to the presence of both the Lincoln Monument and Washington Memorial, tying it physically and historically to the site
.
.
Due pareti di granito nero, poste sotto il livello del suolo, incise in ordine cronologico con i nomi degli uomini e delle donne che hanno dato la vita nella guerra del Vietnam. All'apice in cui si incontrano le due mura, le date 1959 e 1973 (che segnano l'inizio e la fine della guerra) "si incontrano" chiudendo così il cerchio del lasso di tempo della guerra. Un veterano di ritorno può trovare il proprio tempo sul muro, rendendo la propria  esperienza del memoriale molto personale e individuale. L'ubicazione dell'opera è direttamente correlata alla presenza sia del Lincoln Monument che del Washington Memorial, legandolo fisicamente e storicamente al sito
.
.

What art inspires you on campus? @Yale has played a part in fostering the careers of many artists and New Haven is home to an abundance of art. In this new series, we're asking students, faculty, and alumni to share the art on campus that has inspired them the most.
.
Kavitha Bindra ’05, Assistant Dean for Alumni Relations: “Maya Lin was a huge influence on me when I was a student, and she continues to be one of the most innovative and ground-breaking artists out there. She is quietly transgressive and melds a warmth and humanity with the minimalism of her work. She has so much to say and conveys it all so simply and starkly. The Women's Table, which celebrates women at Yale, is one such piece.” [Pictured: Maya Lin, Women’s Table]
.
About Maya Lin's Women's Table at Yale: The Women’s Table can be found in front of Sterling Memorial Library. Commissioned in 1989 by Yale’s former president, Benno Schmidt, Lin (BA ‘81, M.Arch ‘86) created this work to commemorate the first female student at Yale, recognizing the addition (and absence) of women since the university’s founding in 1701 which the artist conveys through the etchings of class years (up until 1993) on the table’s surface. The sculptural installation exemplifies Lin’s minimal design aesthetic, as well as her interest and her experience in art, architecture and public installations. Other notable examples of her past works include the Langston Hughes Library in Tennessee, the Museum of Chinese in America in New York and the Vietnam Memorial in Washington, DC for which she received the National Medal of the Arts in 2009.
